< text>
June 29th 2019. I was racially profiled by the staff and manager while I was there. I had just gotten off of work and I was pretty dirty. I had just walked 5 miles from my job,  i went in to cash my check. When I arrived I waited in line til I was called and proceeded to give the teller my company check along with my ID as is policy. The teller gave me a strange look like I was up to something nefarious, then she handed my check over to her manager. I dont remember her name but I know she was African American and had a British accent.  She told me to go sit down and I did. She then proceeded to go to a closed room. After about 10 minutes she called me up to the front and said aloud in front of everyone, "I need you to leave or I will call the police". As if I were some sort of criminal. I left without incident and notified my manager of the issue. I had to email my HR department and now I'm still waiting on a response. I'm a good guy & I work hard, it really embarrased and me that someone in the customer service industry can so casually dismiss me as a criminal. Now my son has to wait on the things he needs.< /text>

<Text>Now I go here all the time and get my nails done and I say I've been here maybe 25 times. And out of those 25 times maybe two times my mail was not done right. Now when I give these reviews I give it on my own experience. Now as far as getting a pedicure they are excellent. Don't get me wrong a lot of the women there are excellent doing the Nails. I tried someone new. Because someone said I usually one i go to was busy and I was in a rush. After I went to my event the very next day two of the nails popped off. There is one man there and he is excellent in doing nails.. I've been there since then and had no problems. Now I said I keep it real the second problem that I had when I went I took my mother and she had not had her feet done over 10 years. And the reason why is because she has diabetes. So I took her for her birthday to get them done. And I realize they was bad. But that what it's all about when you pick a profession you have to service the customer. And by me going there all the time I didn't think it would be a problem. So we go in they assign the ladies who would do our pedicure. Now the lady that was doing my mom kept talking to this lady next to her about my mom's feet. Of course I can understand her but I know. I also knew buy her face react. At this point I started to get annoyed and some of the other customers to. At the point I said something to the fact look stop talking about my mom feet and do your damn job. Because I am getting annoyed. And the manager  hear me and came over because she knows me and she also know I'm a nice person. <rating>5<//rating>< review>
This place provides ice skating for fun and ice skating for teaching. Even though this place is old and small, I can still have fun no matter what. It is called improvising. This place can be crowded on weekends. I can handle it. What matters is that ice skating is less boring and less quiet. Free lesson of ice skating is definitely worth it. Please take advantage of it for you rookies out there. This place gets an automatic five star for not leaving even though Vallco Shopping Mall is about to get demolished. Improvements are possible. Challenges can be dealt with.<//review>

114978248182006861955</user>
< username>
Billy Manashi<//username>
<Date>1470520035990</Date><Rate>1</Rate>< review>
Went there on a Friday night, the ice skating rink is smaller than other ice skating rinks I have been to. which causes it to become very crowded

There were no employees on the rink managing safety or the flow of traffic. People were skating in all directions. There were several young irresponsible figure skaters recklessly skating and bumping into people.

My friend had to go to the emergency room to get his pinky stitched as a direct result of Ice Center's negligence. There was a young man skating at fast speeds not watching where he was going, he not only caused my friend to trip onto the ice, but he ran over his pinky with his skate right afterward.

I don't think any of these reckless skaters had the intention of hurting people that day, but Ice Center employees should have dealt with them.

After my friend's pinky was sliced open, we proceeded to the front desk to get help. The employees were not trained in basic first-aid and offered no assistance. The only thing they had in their kit of use were band-aids and alcohol wipes. The supervisor in charge was trying to stay away from us and he seemed to not want to get involved. We had to go up to him and ask him to at least give us napkins as my friend's pinky was bleeding quite profusely at this point.

Since we were there for not even 20 minutes before this happened, I asked if my friend and I could at the very least get a refund because I now had to take him to the ER, and the supervisor would not allow it, but instead offered a 'good luck' at the emergency room.

If you care about safety at ice skating rinks then I would look elsewhere.<//review>

<Rating>2</Rating>< Review>
To start off the customer service was great, however, when I received my furniture I had a couple of damages. It was bought from Jerome's furniture (so it wasn't cheap like Ikea), they manage to destroy it through carelessness. It takes a lot of force to destroy the type of furniture that I have, but managed to do it. I did go through claims and contacted the representative who were both gave me excellent service and apologized for the damages. I just wish the workers weren't as rough they are on the furniture I had moved. I recommend getting there insurance coverage, it's a lot more extra but, given the type of people who were moving my stuff, they seem to not have cared one bit.< /Review>

<Review>Just the absolute worst ever. Priority Movers  misplaced our belongings, stole our belongings, did not log in our belongings,  which we got reimbursed for and to this day, there is still a box that according to their former employee Jane Graybill. Shewas not able to find  it and assumes it went off property. On our delivery day, only half of our furniture arrived, half a bed, half a couch, missing lamps, vases ets.  This is when we were told, no one logged in our belongings and therefore could not be found. It was clear that we got the D team because when all of this choas happened, they sent their A team who could not beleive the furniture was assembled incorrectly. The owner came by and took pictures of the poor packing. They dumped our holiday belongings in a box so they could use our plastic bins since they did not bring enough boxes and papers. They somehow looked through all their storage units with our furniture id on it and delivereda while after our original move. We move around a lot and we have gone with big national names such as Mayflower, Allied,  North American but since we wanted to support local b business  and your company was recommended AND more expensive, we thought we would go with Priority. The biggest mistake ever and we will NEVER recommend Priority to any military or non military family that moves a lot. Once we told people that we were also storing off island , everyone said they were not surprised once our belongings went off  and out of town, things would get taken and the last item in were tools and the first item stolen was tools. At least the company kept writing checks for the missing and stolen items. Oddly enough, right when we were to settle and we had been working with the insurance adjuster, Jane Graybill suddently disappears( what a surprises-wink wink) and we start all over with another gal who tells us they cannot put a replacement price on sentimentality. So  china platters got ruined and chipped. They did not wrap just placed in boxes without any paper. We took a whole roll of film of the damage done to the items returned to us.. Priority Movers, never again. They made it very clear they cannot pay for sentimentality but our daughters Mission Project that we had saved over the decades got also crushed..they just stuffed in without wrapping in the middle of a box so it was literally ruined.. It was apparent, that not one employee that packed and moved us could have cared less and only until the A team and the owner of the company saw how we were moved, did they start to care a bit.< /Review>< pictures>

<date>1409024643353< /date><rating>5</rating><Review>Today my wife and I executed a new step in our life moving to our first place that we were able to choose together.  After several months of careful consideration of where to go, choices made, and papers signed we had our things ready to go with one final step.  Who to pick for the big move? We both had to take several days of leave to be able to move out from our downtown apartment to complexes by Kearny Mesa. < review>
Moving is always hard, and there is probably no such thing as a perfect move. Something always gets scratched or bumped, something often gets broken. If all of that is smalls stuff, I consider it a great move.

My husband and I both would say this was a great move. There are two general categories of success from Priority Moving, we think. One is the people and one is your processes. The two work together very successfully.

Andre, Goeffery, and Michael helped us both days (packing and moving), and there were two others who helped one day each (John and Joel). They introduced themselves when they arrived, and Andre who was in the supervisory role began to joke lightly with us, which set the mood. These guys worked hard, kept us informed of what they were doing all the time, finished more quickly than expected, and were fun and interesting to work with. We somehow chose the hottest day of the year to move and yet they kept their senses of humor and hard work ethic going the entire time.

The processes you have in place are followed by everyone, it seems. From receiving a phone call at the front end to confirm times and places and keep us informed, to the way the guys parked the trucks with caution cones, to announcing their breaks, to carefully reviewing paperwork and getting signatures, to receiving mid-afternoon calls to ensure all was going well, you guys clearly care about following tried and true processes for success. And they worked.

We will use Priority Movers again and we will recommend you to others. Thank you for helping us through an exciting and challenging time!< /review>

I am extremely disappointed with Priority Moving.  We used them recently for an in-city move, point-to-point. Several items were damaged due to mishandling, and still others were lost somehow en route. The first problem was that they sent a smaller crew and truck than they promised. They ended up sending a 3-person crew and a smaller truck, which we eventually discovered was not empty to start with, but contained items from another source. This meant they had to make two trips, and instead of taking eight hours it took twelve! They gave us a ‚Äònot to exceed‚Äô price so we didn‚Äôt have to pay extra, but it consumed much more of our time, and that of the crew, than any of us expected.  Than, as we began settling in and unpacking we realized a number of big ticket items were missing (suitcases, a large standing mirror, a bicycle rack, a paper shredder, fireplace tools, etc.)  We called the Priority, and the driver subsequently found some, but not all, of our missing items still in the truck. We also checked with the new owners just in case they moved something, and they had not. So what happened to those items?  I still do not know.  We are still identifying things that didn‚Äôt arrive. For a short point-to-point move they do not create an itemized manifest. <user>100279469988146177635</user><rating>1< /rating>< review>
First, I do not know how they have 4 stars when they have deleted or labeled reviews not recommended. Secondly, they are contracted with Arpin Van Lines.

*There is a lack of communication
*Lie about delivery window (please see other reviews,mostly those not recommended)
*No one know how to get a hold of the driver and cannot call dispatch directly. Can't they radio him?
*It takes days for them to relay information after customer initial contact.
*The lack of accountability of the driver is why customer things end up missing.
*They take on other contracts after customer pick up which is why they do not make there delivery window.

Unfortunately, I did not do my homework as I usually do prior to signing a contract. That was the biggest mistake and has cause much headache and stress. I had someone come out and do a home estimate. The person was friendly and professional. The gentleman Don Carlson was eager to get our business. They even lowered the price by applying a bunch of discounts. Because this was a personal move without the military, we were looking for something cheap, but *remember* you get what you pay for.

Prior to pick up, I notified Priority I needed an extra stop and was told to talk to the driver. On the day of pick up, a driver arrived (I never received prior notification as to when they would be coming) and took inventory and loaded our things. He was not friendly at all. I notified him of the extra stop and I was told I would be contacted by the driver who would be actually handling our furniture. I never received the weight of the furniture until the 3rd day. I actually had to call Ms. Christina D. She said she had to get back to me (which is a way too common phrase.

My items were picked up on April 11th and I was given a delivery time frame of April 13 and April 21. In between that I  had not heard from anyone and called Christina to find out about delivery. She has no clue where the driver was. It took a day or two to get back to me about our shipment. I was told the driver was a week behind schedule and my things would not be delivered until April 28th. No one bothered to contact me about the delay and no one had information when I kept calling. I got tired of going through the middle man and asked for Arpin Van Lines contact. I talked to Chris Kumkin out of headquarters and he was not able to get information.

On April 22nd I was contacted to say my things would be delivered on the 26th. On the 25th I called to confirm things were still on schedule and Arpin had no clue where the driver is and she would have to get back to me.

I have only move with one other company (United Van Lines). I had a couple things missing, but I ALWAYS had communication with the drive via his cell phone and things were always delivered within 2-3 days.

For the people that work at Priority and Arpin Van Line, you should be ashamed to work for such a poor and irresponsible company<//review>

<review>We stayed here for NYE and a few days after that -- I had booked this hotel months in advance. When we got there, there was an unusual amount of security which I didn't mind. We ended up finding out Justin Bieber was performing a concert there that evening (we didn't know or care). We were paying hotel guests (rooms are upwards of $350/night), but had to go through metal detectors with our belongings searched everytime we left the lobby. We were constantly questioned if we needed to leave the property (to get food or just drive around the city). We were constantly asked to show our room key before allowing us into a HALLWAY where our room was situated, and treated as subpar by the staff and hotel concierge, just because we didn't pay to see Bieber, but instead were just "regular" paying hotel guests with someone monitoring every move we made (not allowed to walk around the hotel or even in the parking garage to get to our car -- we had to be escorted). I understand he's a celebrity, but this hotel's guests should not be treated as inferior just because we're not famous. Such a disappointing experience. Also, no amenities. The maid service and room with a balcony were wonderful. The staff helpful. I loved that both Hanukkah and Christmas were being celebrated with arrangements . The turn down service was very sweet. Only reason I did not give this hotel a 5 star rating was breakfast. At breakfast on the patio I had to actively try to get someone‚Äôs attention for service for more tea and food.  That was a downer of an experience that I was not expecting. I would definitely stay there again. The bartender was super sweet. The room, immaculate and very well appointed.</Review>

<text>There are hotels out there that are newer, more luxurious and offer higher-end amenities, but they still will not match the level of elegance, sophistication and rich history that this hotel has to offer. Time spent here is not a stay,  it's an experience. Management and staff know it and try to cater to it and that sets them apart from any other resort. There's always something going on at the Beverly Hilton: a gala, a fundraiser or a function of somekind that bring out the one percent in droves. So much has gone on here over the years that if walls could talk, they would tell a story that could easily trump the best of what Hollywood screen writers have to offer. The food is very well made and the service is terrific but that's almost a side note to the main event: a history lesson with a healthy dose of (rich) people-watching.</text><Pictures>[{'url': Nice venue for our meeting. Good food, nice people, good security. I noticed the remodel is done and it looks great. Pictures on the wall great.

Past visits the patio restaurant is very good. Very casual. Didn't get to try that this meeting.

If you have a truck or large car you might want valet  parking since the ramps in the self park are narrow.

The best is the concierge who helped four tired hungry men decide where to go for dinner. She is charming, witty and knows the area very well :)< /text>

<username>Mini Rag< /username><Date>1569812458894<//Date><Rate>3<//Rate>< Review>
An iconic Los Angeles hotel, with sprinkling of the old charm all over the place. The lobby, the balrooms etc. are all well appointed. The fish acqarium is next to the elevators is wonderful.

Rooms are a bit small, at $400 per night. The bed was comfortable. The ac in the room had a mind of its own. You have to call down for turn down service (weird), but they did not come and do it. The bathroom has covered separate toilet and shower, great.

There is a Starbucks behind the lobby where you can eat breakfast, the juice is $12 but rest is affordable.< /Review>

<user>109014684534572732250< /user>< Review>
I enjoyed my time at this hotel for two reasons.

1. Location, location location!
It's within walking distance of Rodeo Drive and other attractions.

2. The People who work there.
I've stopped in a lot of different hotels in the USA and I really liked how genuine the lady at the check-in desk came across when welcoming us to stay with them. It didn't stop there as everyone we spoke with in the hotel were great and I know customer service is big in the USA but in this hotel they came across like they really did care.

For both of these reasons I would consider going back here again and if you're offered the opportunity to upgrade to the new block with a balcony make sure you do it as you won't regret it.</Review>

< review>
Very dated feel -- like an older Las Vegas property. This was the first time I had ever stayed here, so I was kind of shocked, truthfully. Our room was nice, although there was no bathtub. You'd think for the price, plus the fact that dur to Covid there were VERY few people staying at the hotel, they would give us a room with a bathtub as we REQUESTED when we made our reservation. They also bunched booked rooms close together (again strange considering the hotel was sparsely booked), so the loud laughter from the room next door spoiled the evening a little as well. They also charged us $50 a night to park our car -- which wasn't made known to us at the time of booking. That's an offensive amount at this time. Overall, a pretty so-so, yawn experience. Would never go back.< /review>

<review>Let me start off by saying this is an iconic, luxury hotel. It's amazing and truly represents the Beverly Hills lifestyle, in many ways! So much to do around the hotel onsite and off site! The rooms are spacious and the decor is nice. If you get a suite, you most likely will have a balcony overlooking either Santa Monica Blvd, or Wilshire road I believe. Staying in a corner suite, the views were pretty good and my balcony was OVERSIZED.  Glass almost all over the room, felt great to wake up to that! TV in the bathroom and nice tub, and shower as well, bathroom amenities included a vanity mirror and in bathroom TV. There was an iPad in the room where you could request items, order room service, ask for concierge help, arrange dry cleaning services, and much much more! Its also personalized with their hotel system so it knows your name and the weather report is listed for you as well. Truly a great Hilton hotel! Whats more to love? You get plentiful of options for room types as well. Suites, and room in the Oasis building which offer a different type of ambiance. NOTE: Ask for Yamileth at the front desk! Shes amazing, and very helpful. < Review>
Beautiful hotel, only thing is our deluxe twin room seemed the same size as a regular. Only thing could be that the bathroom may have been bigger. Your room does come with free water but of course the free water is located in the fridge that has a key. We thought the water (2 bottles; 1 regular 1 sparkling) on the table by the ice bucket and cups were free. Nope those cost together $23. Sorry didn't think the free water had to be locked up. So free water in locked fridge with unlimited refills from front desk. Hotel reimbursed our water charges. We also like to leave the do not disturb sign on the door when we leave so service is not needed to go in our room where our belongings are. (Keeping the hotel honest) Well they still did! They apologized and comped one of our $45 parking fee. Parking is $45 for Valet or self parking. Yes both same price. All in all View from the 7th floor was beautiful. Will return but unfortunately not soon.<//Review>

<rate>5<//rate>< text>
This hotel offers 5 star service no doubt. We were originally put in a room that faced a construction zone and was very noisy, no balcony. We called down to the front desk and asked if they had another room available and they upgraded us to a larger room with a balcony and overlooking the city and the pool. It was fabulous! The restaurant in the hotel was delicious, the staff are all wonderful here. We sat by the pool in the morning around 9am and did not realize there is no poolside service until 11am, but the staff still brought us coffee and menus beside the pool anyways. Fabulous hotel.</text>

<user>108506577932627935985< /user><Name>Rachel Kienzler</Name><time>1538202852322< /time><Rating>3</Rating>< Text>
I've been here a few times (not my bookings). Nice hotel, but a bit over-hyped.  The rooms are nothing special (not for the rates they charge; non-conference rates). Sometimes, feels like the staff is only friendly when they think you will be spending money. Example: I pulled up front in a standard rental car on the day I was checking out and the valet was completely dismissive of me before I had even put the car in park. They no longer have a spa on site, which is just silly for a hotel like this. One time that we stayed here, there were fleas in our room, apparently from some pet-friendly convention the week before, and the hotel didn't even offer to cover the cost of of taking our clothes to cleaners (we didn't want to chance bringing any of the critters back to our home...which is only about an hour from this hotel, and where we have no pets so wouldn't have otherwise had fleas in our home). Oh, and the pool area at this hotel is nothing special. I have stayed in many 5-star resorts/hotels, and they were better.
Okay, I have to say something positive - the food is very good.  The historic elements of the hotel are cool, it has a good Hollywood/Beverly Hills vibe, and very good conference space (though the rooms get very cols, so bring a jacket). Also, aside from the spa, it has all the services and amenities important in a large hotel</Text>

<UserId.>114045822380624490762< /UserId.>< rating>

<resp>None<//resp></record>
</dataset><record>
< review>
I recently stayed a couple of nights here. My room was conveniently placed, overlooking the pool and close to the first floor parking. That much was pleasing. The room itself was quite large but otherwise unexceptional, and with a few significant defects. The bedside lamp failed to work, and despite a service request via the iPad ordering system (which was acknowledged with an in-house text) nothing was done about this by engineering until the second night, when I phoned in my request. This was then, it is true, immediately taken care of, but it was really a case of too little, too late. Of all the lights in the room, that to me is the most crucial (one other bulb was out, but that was insignificant). I was also bothered by the piped Christmas music, quite loud and very audible in the room, drifting in from the pool area. As I turned in early, this was an unfortunate annoyance.

The room furniture was worn and tired, with a couple of knobs almost detached. The beds were comfortable, and the bathroom was clean and serviceable. Room service was prompt (I ate in the first night, having traveled all day), but the room service menu was a bit uninspired and ultimately dispiriting, and of surprisingly mediocre quality in terms of both ingredients and preparation. On the second night I had a pleasant drink by the pool (which I did not use during my stay) and that was perhaps the nicest memory from my stay. The staff were all courteous and helpful, and I would not fault them at all (except in the matter of the room lights), and the convenience of the location (an easy drive from the airport, even in rush hour) is hard to beat, but taken all in all, this was a disappointing stay. I'd not willingly repeat it.</review>

< Text>
Mmy best stay ever
annually hosts the Golden Globe Awards

Some say rooms could benefit from a refresh

The Beverly Hilton is a classic, but some say it can't keep up with the newest, hippest hotels of¬†Los Angeles. In fact, it's probably better known as the home of the Golden Globe Awards (which take place annually in the International Ballroom) than it is as a place to spend the night. However, the 569 rooms ‚Äì which feature Egyptian cotton linens, Bose Wave music systems and BABOR Beauty toiletries ‚Äì hint at luxury, though some guests say that the accommodations here feel dated. The hotel staff, on the other hand, earns props from visitors, who say that The Beverly Hilton's employees were friendly and efficient.</Text>

I have stayed here MANY times. The rooms vary in size, but all of them are nice. Staying in the Cabana pool rooms is a very different feel. <Review>My wife and I stayed over the weekends on the 7th floor one bed hotel room. It had a patio surprisingly but the view was not that good as our room was facing inward into other hotels. As being an old hotel, the room shows some signs of age however it was clean and service was excellent. When we first arrived, they served us with some welcome snacks. We weren't particularly keen on sweets so we didn't eat much of it but the gesture is appreciated. The parking is not free as it is LA, but that was to be expected. The Rodeo was close by, about 10-15 minutes walk. The hotel pool was kinda full most of the time (very hot weather) so we didn't bother visiting. The area around is mostly clean and good for shoppers if you're into luxury brands. We mostly eyeshopped and had dinner at 208 Rodeo restaurant. Overall we enjoyed our stay. It has much history and was an interesting place to stay.<//Review>< user_id>

< Text>
OMG, it was a charity event. The staff was so attentive and polite. Not sure if it was all the Hilton or not, but so well planned out. Food was vegan and very good. I had to wear a suit to get in, oh well third time for me.
Very pleasant people with trays of tasty little snacks wondering around the crowds people. If asked they would describe exactly what it was. If you liked it they would make sure to track you down with the next round. Open bar, just got a few Cokes, I had to drive.
The dining room was spacious and had a few large screens and a large stage at one end. Never an issue seeing or hearing anything. All very well planned out and a great support team.
I have been to many events at other venues and this one was one of the best ones in memory as far as execution. I'm sure some percentage was the event planner and some the Hilton. I give them both a lot of credit, it was a memorable event.<//Text>

<Rate>4< /Rate><Review>I attended a professional event hosted in this venue, so my experiences are limited to those in the main banquet hall right by the pool and self-park elevators.

It was a breakfast event. The food provided was good, and service was great. We had to wait a while for the servers to give our food, but thereafter they have been responsive and prompt.

The venue looked very nice, especially the ceilings embedded chandeliers. I liked the stage and presentation area - 3 screens seem to do the trick. Restrooms were also nice and clean.

There came a point when the emergency alarm sounded, and staff over the intercom communicated somewhat effectively - they had not statused with the guests whether it was an accidental pull, or if something wrong was really happening. Really made the people in the venue paranoid, some seemed to leave just to ensure their own safety!

The parking can use a lot of work. The garage is super cramped and there is little room for movement.<//Review>< pictures>

The efficiency of the on-site hotel reservation department is horrible.  I've made the same reservation multiple times and they've messed it up everytime. So now, 3 cancellations later and 1 re-booking. I thought it was right.  I had to speak with the Front Desk Manager, Hairston, who was the only bright light throughout this entire experience.  I give him a 5-star!   In re-booking my reservation, I added a room for my elderly relative and requested they be in the same tower.  I was told this was done. This representative made the change ( to my specifications I think), but it seemed as though he had something better to do as he rushed me through the call and hung up before I could get him name. <Text>Oops I did it again. I really used to love the Beverly Hilton. When we started our US entity, we had our office on 600 Century Park East, so I lived there for months - and really loved it.

< rating>
1<//rating>
<Review>I stayed here recently and the service at this hotel is abysmal! I visit LA often and usually stay in WEHO, but decided to try somewhere different as we were a larger group. There is a complete lack of communication between management and staff and as a result nothing gets done and no one knows what's going on. During our four night stay we had to call for assistance on at least 13 occasions for reasons ranging from blocked toilets to room not being made up and also because the whole handle to operate the shower fell off. On each occasion several calls had to be made to reception as the request was never actioned. Each person would pass the blame to someone else. It's very frustrating having to spend so much time on the phone to reception to fix substandard facilities.  This hotel hosts many large corporate events, as was evident during our stay there. At these times we were made to feel like second class citizens. We were not allowed to enter or exit through the main entrance and were ushered out the back entrance with rubbish and cigarettes strewn all over the place. They also take a very long time to clean up after hosting events, with wine glasses and cigarettes still left on tables in common areas 24 hours later! This hotel is in need of a total
refurbishment, but more importantly,  management need to be booted out and overhauled with a more professional and efficient team who can make changes and run the facility effectively. Guests can often overlook dated facilities if personal service is exceptional,  as how one is treated will always leave a lasting impression! Unfortunately this hotel is nowhere near Hilton standards, they have a great deal of work to do to improve themselves overall. Spend your dollars elsewhere !</Review><Pics>None< /Pics>< response>
None< /response>

I often host events at this hotel for clients.  It is a great location for parties both formal and not.  What makes the hotel unique is of course it's history in entertainment.  If you are a tourist or Hollywood fan you will love it's decor. You might even get s chance to meet or see a celeb.  In addition, I've always had a pleasant stay in the rooms.  Even when I'm not on official business I love to stay at this hotel.  Now if your. <UserId.>102200955263714225332< /UserId.>< Response>
None<//Response>
< Review>
I am sorry that in some cases this hotel has garnered unjustifiable bad reviews. I was born in 1963 and have been coming to this hotel with family since 1972. Although I now live back east my uncle and aunt still live on North Linden Drive in Beverly Hills. We always go there for lunch after mass at Church of the Good Sheppard whenever I am in town.

The staff is all courteous and helpful even though we are not guests of the hotel but over time have either had party(s) or other activities at the Beverly Hilton.

When I was in the service and arrived in Beverly Hills only to find that my uncle and aunt were away the staff made a young man in the service feel right at home.

Everyone at the Beverly Hilton hotel is top notch.

Continued success.< /Review>

<user_id>109703354157678606170< /user_id><Name>Person N Cary<//Name><Date>1534707675180</Date><rate>3< /rate><Text>Had 1 night to be near BH, chose this based upon my HHonors status, use of points, and as others have said "It's Iconic status in BH". Room in Wilshire tower was solid....good bed, sheets, towels, bath amentities, etc. had a good nights sleep. The view was eh....couldn't see much on 4th floor other than other buildings. The service wasn't great....not that it was awful (I didn't experience the indignation as others have mentioned), it's just that they didn't do the usual things I see at most Hilton properities. No HHonors line at the front desk...line was long (8 parties deep) only 2 people working the front desk, no one called for additional help. Comp breakfast at 55 was also solid, and service kind of same...while we were seated promptly, we weren't told about the buffet (I noticed someone else bringing an omelet back to their table, so went up and asked...yep, they have an omelet station but chef doesn't station it unless someone asks). Oh, valet parking is busy...glad they had self-park...at one point while we were out front waiting to be picked up by a relative, just marveled at the inefficiency and resulting log jams from not having enough attendants. Probably won't stay again.<//Text><Pics>None</Pics><Resp>None<//Resp>< GmapID>

<Text>I love, love, love The Beverly Hilton. The only place we stay when we go to LA. Convenient to everything (by LA standards). Pay a little extra and get a room with a balcony. Starbucks franchise in the lobby off to the left as you enter; it's also a bar and they probably serve alcohol at 7 AM but I don't know about that.

It's built on a little slope so there are a couple of subterranean levels, which have a big pool area and cabanas and the last remaining Trader Vic's in the country. The food is disgusting but it's fun. Also, and it's kind of difficult to get to, there's a top-floor restaurant somewhere in the complex where we always get complementary brunch passes to and it was the original home of L'Escoffier. I always feel Don Draper-ish walking in there, even though the patrons are 21st-century overweight tourists from America and abroad.

Can't recommend it enough.</Text><time>1436623210443</time><username>Bob Blake</username></record>

<Text>the golden globes< /Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMJ1hN_XeNb-K9ADGtQpV4zc2MDM-tUaV6Kw34y=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures><response>None< /response>< gmapID>

<UserId.>100590706299143970785<//UserId.><Name>Jake B< /Name>< Time>
1432018698952< /Time>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
My experience at the hotel was marvelous, full of nostalgia of old Hollywood, and glimpses of would-be celebrities walking about. The front desk greets you warmly (I had already checked in on my phone), so i just needed a room key. After being directed to our room, we left the lobby and walked around the surroundings, enjoying the small shops and such on our way to the elevator. The floor we were on was extremely clean, with pictures of old Hollywood actors and actresses that had stayed at the hotel.  We were celebrating my mom's birthday, and it was neat to know the hotel opened the same year my mom was born. Anyway, the rooms were small-ish, but stilll adequate for two adults. The beds were typical Hilton property beds, aka AMAZING. That's the best part of a stay at a Hilton, you know. The TV had tons of regular channels, there were vending and ice machines in the hall, and everything else was fairly status quo. However, the aspect of the Beverly Hilton that will put you in that cosmic, nostalgic, embraced-in-luxury feeling is the bar and pool area. Getting an original mai tai at Trader Vic's sitting at an outdoor lounge overlooking the pool area, wondering what famous people I'm unknowingly looking at....smoking a cigarette on the 2nd story balcony smoking area with  plush chairs and a great view of the pool area really made it a 5-star stay for us, The ambiance was absolutely unmatched! We were only there a night but I hope to stay many more nights in the future! I would take off 1/4 star if I could just because there's no refrigerator in the rooms, which sucks for me because I gotta have a morning Monster energy drink. Also, the sliding door separating the bedroom area from the bathroom area is very flimsy and provides little to no sound-proofing, and thus no real privacy. Someone in bed can hear every single slight noise that goes on in the bathroom in far too much detail. Hilton, please do something about that! Even the closest of couples don't want to hear each other poo. Seriously.</text>
